    The TransferFunction for our nullability analysis. This analysis determines, for all variables and parameters, whether they are definitely null (NullnessValue.NULL), definitely non-null (NullnessValue.NONNULL), possibly null (NullnessValue.NULLABLE), or are on an infeasible path (NullnessValue.BOTTOM). This analysis depends only on the code and does not take nullness annotations into account.

    Each visit*() implementation provides us with information about nullability that applies if the expression is successfully evaluated (in other words, it did not throw an exception). For example, if foo.toString() is successfully evaluated, we know two things:

    1. The expression itself is non-null (because toString() is in our whitelist of methods known to return non-null values)
    2. foo is non-null (because it has been dereferenced without producing a NullPointerException)

    These particular two pieces of data also demonstrate the two connected but distinct systems that we use to track nullness:

    1. We compute the nullability of each expression by applying rules that may reference only the nullability of subexpressions. We make the result available only to superexpressions (and to the final output of the analysis).
    2. We update and read the nullability of variables in a mapping that persists from node to node. This is the only exception to the rule that we propagate data from subexpression to superexpression only. The mapping is read only when visiting a LocalVariableNode. That is enough to give the LocalVariableNode a value that is then available to superexpressions.

    A further complication is that sometimes we know the nullability of an expression only conditionally based on its result. For example, foo == null proves that foo is null in the true case (such as inside if (foo == null) { ... }) and non-null in the false case (such an inside an accompanying else block). This is handled by methods that accept multiple LocalVariableUpdates instances, one for the true case and one for the false case.
